"meanings":["Medieval French variant of   Bertram  , imported to Britain by the Normans. In modern times it has been made famous by the English philosopher  Bertrand Russell  (  1872–1970 ), but is only in occasional use."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Comte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jean Jacques.","French:","nickname for someone in the service of a count or for someone who behaved pretentiously, from Old French <i>conte</i>, <i>cunte</i> ‘count’. In North America, this surname is also a shortened form of the French cognate   Lecomte  . Compare   Conte   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Lecomte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Monique, Normand, Alain, Armand, Cecile, Dominique, Francois, Germain, Gilles, Gregoire, Huguette, Pierre.","French and Walloon: nickname for someone in the service of a count or for someone who behaved pretentiously, from Old French <i>conte</i>, <i>cunte</i> ‘count’, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Compare   Comte   1.","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Le Comte</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bertrand Comte Forcalquier was born about 1109, in Forcalquier, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France as the son of Guillem I de Urgell Comte de Forcalquier et de Niza. He had at least 1 son with Josserande de la Flotte. He died about 1150, at the age of 43."},"et":{"abt 1109–abt 1150":"umbes 1109–umbes 1150","1109–1150":"1109–1150","1110–1151":"1110–1151","1130–1209":"1130–1209","1085–1129":"1085–1129","1129":"1129","7 octobre 1129":"7. oktoober 1129","abt 1109":"umbes 1109","abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1151":"1151","1150":"1150","1209":"1209","1109":"1109","Forcalquier, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence, France":"Forcalquier, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence, Provence